"Abt. 1124":"about 1124","1109":"1109","Great Torrington, Devon, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Torrington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name, mainly from Black, Great, or Little Torrington (Devon).","2  English: in Lincs and E Anglia from East or West Torrington (Lincs), recorded as  <i>Terintone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Tiringtuna</i> about 1115, or from Terrington (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Tirintuna</i> between 1103 and 1131."],"variants":[{"name":"Tarrington","meanings":["1  English: locative name, variant of   Torrington  .","2  English: locative name, perhaps sometimes from Tarrington (Herefs), but there is no clear link between the 1379 example and the 18th-century Staffs and Lancs name cited below, which may instead belong with (1)."]},{"name":"Terrington","meanings":["1  English: locative name, in S Lincs and E Anglia a variant of   Torrington   (2).","2  English: locative name in N England from Terrington (NR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Torrington I was born in 1109, in Great Torrington, Devon, England, his father, Robert de Torrington, was 14 and his mother, Mrs. Robert de Torrington, was 19. He married Mable Tyldesley. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1170, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1109–1170":"1109–1170","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1113–1150":"1113–1150","1124–1157":"1124–1157","1134–1170":"1134–1170","1095–1115":"1095–1115","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1090":"1090","1095":"1095","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1113":"1113","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","Abt. 1124":"umbes 1124","1109":"1109","Great Torrington, Devon, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1109–1170":"1109–1170","1105–Male":"1105–Kuollut","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1113–1150":"1113–1150","1124–1157":"1124–1157","1134–1170":"1134–1170","1095–1115":"1095–1115","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1090":"1090","1095":"1095","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1157":"1157","1124":"1124","1113":"1113","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","Abt. 1124":"noin 1124","1109":"1109","Great Torrington, Devon, England":"Great Torrington, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1109–1170":"1109–1170","1105–Male":"1105–Décédé","1135–Male":"1135–Décédé","1113–1150":"1113–1150","1124–1157":"11